ce:section.ce:para:
Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) is a characterization technique that was used for characterization of stepwise modification of modified electrodes at each immobilization step at a frequency range of 0.1 to100 kHz in a solution of 5mM [Fe(CN)6]3−/4−, as a redox probe, and 0.1M KCl (at a ratio of 1:1). EIS plots were obtained at a potential of 0.25V, for bare GCE (a) GQD-SH/GCE (b), AuNPs/GQD-SH/GCE (c), Apt/AuNPs/GQD-SH/GCE (d), BSA/Apt/AuNPs/GQD-SH/GCE (e). EIS plots (Fig. 1
                        ) of different electrodes were recorded based on this technique. The charge transfer resistance (Rct) is a key parameter for the kinetics of a probe that shows the immobilization of the substrates onto the modified electrode surface in each step of the process. Randles equivalent circuit RS (Cdl Rct) was used to fit the experimental data. Rs is the solution resistance, Rct is the electron-transfer resistance, Cdl is the double layer capacitance (Inner Fig. 1). As shown in Fig. 1, After casting some of GQD-SH on the surface of GCE, Rct value increased from 600Ω for the bare GCE (Curve a) to 1500Ω for the GQD-SH/GCE (Curve b). The existence of the thiol and hydroxyl groups in the structure of the GQD-SH leads to negative partial charge of this nanomaterial. Therefore, the presence of the negative partial charge on the GCE surface leads to [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− repulsion and decrease in electron transfer (eT). In the next step, when AuNPs was dropped on the surface of the electrode, Rct value increased to ~2950Ω (Curve c). AuNPs with negative charge, immobilized onto the SH groups of GQDs via bonding formation of AuS, led to repulsion between the negatively charged [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− anions and the AuNPs to the extent that the response of redox probe was reduced, thereby increasing the Rct value. In the next step, as expected, according to Curve d, Rct was increased to 7950Ω by loading the STR specific Apt on the electrode surface. This increase in value indicated that the covalent attachment of the thiol-Apt onto the AuNPs surface took place through the formation of a favored AuS bond between the thiol group of the Apt and the AuNPs. Due to the negative charges of the phosphate groups in the Apt molecules, the eT of the redox probe was prevented and the extent of the probe response was reduced. Similar increase could also be observed when BSA solution was dropped onto the surface of electrode (Curve e, Rct
                        =13,050Ω). The increased resistance in Curve “e” can be attributed to the reduction of available active sites and the effective surface area for electron transfer process by BSA. Consequently, the proposed aptasensor has been constructed successfully. The cyclic voltammetry (CV) technique is a favored technique to study layer by layer immobilization of the modified electrodes. Fig. S3 shows the typical CV responses of the modified electrodes in each step in 5mM [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− which includes KCl (0.1M). First, a CV of the bare electrode was recorded (voltammogram curve a). Secondly, when the GQD-SH was dropped onto the surface of the electrode, the peak current decreased which is attributed to repelling between negative partial charge of GQD-SH and the probe. Thus, this phenomena lead to the inhibition of eT between redox probe and the electrode surface (voltammogram b). Thirdly, when the AuNPs were immobilized onto the thiol groups of the GQD-SH, which forms a self-assemble monolayer via AuS bonds, due to the negative charge, they prevented the eT of redox probe and increase in the peak potential separation accrued to the decrease of the peak current (voltammogram c). Fourth, when the STR specific Apt was placed on the electrode surface, a cluster of long spacer arms on the platform is formed, resulting in more blocking of the electron flow of probe to the electrode surface. Thus, the CV response decreased (voltammogram d). This can be attributed to the repulsion between the negative charges of the phosphate groups in the Apt and redox probe anions. Finally, the CV response decreased with the dropping of BSA solution onto electrode surface (voltammogram e). This is attributed to the reduction of available active sites for electron transfer process by protein. The obtained DPV (Fig. S4) data corroborate the preceding results obtained by EIS and CV, all of them confirm that the sensing interface is successfully achieved.

The stability of the developed sensor was investigated by the CV techniques. The CVs related to the modified electrode, revealed that the modified electrode retained about 98.9% of its initial response, after 50 repetitive cycles (Fig. S5). In addition, the storage stability of the modified electrode was very good as the electrode was found to be 85% of its initial activity for 10days when kept at 4°C. Furthermore, reproducibility of the electrodes was investigated. The peak current response of the modified electrode was determined with 5 electrodes which were produced under the same conditions. The response peak intensity showed a relative standard deviation (RSD) of 3.5% confirming that the results are reproducible (Fig. 4
                        ). Selectivity of the fabricated aptasensor as a very important characteristic in human serum sample was estimated. Hence, as shown in Fig. 5
                        , the DPV responses were recorded for interfering species such as amoxicillin, ciprofloxacin, gentamicin, on the modified electrode at the concentration of 10ng·ml−1 for each interferences in the presence of 100pg·ml−1 of STR. There was no significant changes towards the several interferences.
